Context:
At lines 213-226 in platform/mcp-server/src/index.ts:
```typescript
const handleListenError = (error: unknown): never => {
  const isAddrInUse = error instanceof Error && 'code' in error && error.code === 'EADDRINUSE';
  if (isAddrInUse) {
    log.error(`Port ${PORT} is already in use. ...`);
    // platform-specific cleanup hints...
    log.error(`  PORT=<number> opentabs start`);
  }
  throw error;  // ← THIS causes the raw stack trace
};
```
The `throw error` at line 225 is outside the `if (isAddrInUse)` block, so it runs for ALL errors including EADDRINUSE. When thrown from inside a top-level `await` (line 257: `const server = ... ?? (await createHttpServer())`), it becomes an unhandled rejection and Node.js prints the full stack trace.

Changes:
```typescript
const handleListenError = (error: unknown): never => {
  const isAddrInUse = error instanceof Error && 'code' in error && error.code === 'EADDRINUSE';
  if (isAddrInUse) {
    log.error(`Port ${PORT} is already in use. Kill the existing process or use a different port:`);
    // ... platform-specific hints ...
    log.error(`  PORT=<number> opentabs start`);
    process.exit(1);
  }
  throw error;  // Non-EADDRINUSE errors still propagate
};
```
`process.exit(1)` satisfies the `never` return type since it terminates the process.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the error message text or platform-specific hints
- Keep `throw error` in the non-EADDRINUSE path for other unexpected errors
- The function return type `never` is still satisfied by both `process.exit(1)` and `throw error`
